description.undefined: Integration testing ensures that different components work correctly when combined. It focuses on data flow, API interactions, and communication between modules

example.value: API integration tests, database connectivity tests, module interaction tests, service-to-service communication tests

comment.undefined: Testing combined components

description.undefined: Programming languages are the fundamental tools for implementing the system logic, algorithms, and functionality. Different languages may be used for different components of the project

definition.value: A formal language with syntax and semantics used to write computer programs for the FYP

example.value: Python, Java, JavaScript, C++, PHP, TypeScript, C#, Swift, Kotlin, Go

comment.undefined: Programming languages used in development

description.undefined: The coordinator conducts weekly classes, assigns deliverables, monitors progress, and holds 60% of total marks (120/200) in the grading process

definition.value: Faculty member who manages the FYP course, allocates tasks, and evaluates student performance

comment.undefined: FYP coordinator who manages the course

description.undefined: Research projects involve conducting literature reviews, developing methodologies, performing experiments, and analyzing results. Despite the research focus, they still require implementation deliverables

definition.value: A type of FYP focused on investigating research questions through experimentation and analysis

comment.undefined: Research-focused project

description.undefined: End users are the target audience for the FYP deliverable, whose needs and requirements drive the project's functional specifications

definition.value: Individuals who will interact with and use the final product or system developed in the FYP

comment.undefined: End users of the application

description.undefined: If a project is incomplete, the committee may allow revisions to the existing project or submission of a new proposal within 2 weeks, providing students with a contingency path

definition.value: Procedures and options available when a project is deemed incomplete or unsuccessful

comment.undefined: Plan for handling incomplete projects

description.undefined: Interface requirements define how the system will interact with users, hardware, software, and other systems, establishing clear boundaries and communication protocols

definition.value: A section of the SRS that specifies all interfaces between the system and external entities

comment.undefined: External Interface Requirements section

description.undefined: The design document includes various diagrams such as Data Flow Diagrams (DFD), UML sequence diagrams, class diagrams, entity-relationship diagrams, and architectural views that illustrate how the system will be constructed

definition.value: A comprehensive document that describes the system architecture, design patterns, and technical specifications

example.value: Contains DFD Level 0, Level 1, ER diagrams, sequence diagrams, component diagrams

comment.undefined: Contains diagrams like DFD, sequence diagrams, etc.

description.undefined: The implementation phase involves either coding and testing for development projects or experimentation for research projects. This phase spans across Capstone I and II and includes mid-semester evaluations

definition.value: The phase where the actual system is built through coding and testing, or research experiments are conducted

comment.undefined: System implementation, coding, or experimentation

description.undefined: Usability testing focuses on the user experience, including interface design, navigation flow, accessibility, and overall user satisfaction. It often involves real users performing typical tasks

definition.value: Documentation of tests that evaluate how easy and pleasant the system is for users to interact with

example.value: User task completion tests, navigation flow analysis, accessibility compliance tests, user satisfaction surveys, heuristic evaluations

comment.undefined: Testing user experience

description.undefined: Alternate scenarios describe what happens when things don't go as expected in the main flow, including error conditions, alternative choices, or exceptional circumstances

definition.value: A variation from the main scenario that handles exceptions, errors, or alternative paths

example.value: Invalid login credentials entered, network connection lost, insufficient permissions, user cancels operation

comment.undefined: Alternative flow of events in a use case

description.undefined: Hardware interface requirements detail the characteristics of hardware devices, including sensors, actuators, storage devices, network equipment, and other physical components that interact with the software system

definition.value: Specifications for physical devices and hardware components that the system must interface with

example.value: Printer specifications, scanner requirements, GPS module interfaces, camera requirements, minimum RAM/CPU specifications

comment.undefined: Device requirements

description.undefined: For development projects, this phase includes creating Software Requirement Specifications (SRS) and Software Design Specifications (SDS). For research projects, this involves literature review and developing the proposed methodology

definition.value: The phase where students create detailed specifications for development projects or research methodologies for research projects

comment.undefined: Phase for developing specifications or research methodology

description.undefined: Criteria define the specific aspects to be evaluated and the standards for measuring success. They provide objective measures for consistent and fair assessment across different projects

definition.value: Specific standards or benchmarks used to measure and evaluate different aspects of the FYP

example.value: Technical complexity, innovation, code quality, documentation completeness, presentation skills, project management, problem-solving approach

comment.undefined: Evaluation criteria used for assessment

description.undefined: Performance testing measures system responsiveness, stability, scalability, and resource usage under different workloads. It includes load testing, stress testing, and endurance testing

definition.value: Documentation of tests that evaluate system performance under various load conditions

example.value: Load tests, stress tests, response time measurements, throughput analysis, resource utilization tests, scalability tests

comment.undefined: Testing system performance

description.undefined: Unit testing focuses on verifying the functionality of individual modules, functions, or classes. These tests are typically automated and run frequently during development to catch bugs early

definition.value: Documentation of tests performed on individual units or components of the system in isolation

example.value: Function-level tests, class method tests, module tests, test cases for individual APIs, mock object tests

comment.undefined: Testing individual components

description.undefined: The project timeline includes the Spring semester for proposal submission and approval, Fall semester (Capstone I) for implementation start and mid-semester evaluation, and Spring semester (Capstone II) for final implementation, demo, and comprehensive report submission

definition.value: The chronological structure of the FYP spanning approximately 270 days across multiple semesters

comment.undefined: Timeline for the entire FYP process

description.undefined: Use cases document the interactions between users (actors) and the system, describing the steps needed to accomplish specific tasks. They form a key part of requirements analysis and system design

definition.value: A description of how a user will interact with the system to achieve a specific goal

comment.undefined: Represents user interactions with the system

definition.value: An individual or entity that has an interest in or is affected by the FYP

comment.undefined: Any person or role involved in the FYP process

example.value: User is logged in, Order is placed in database, Email confirmation is sent, User profile is updated

example.value: Response time under 3 seconds, 99.9% uptime, support for 1000 concurrent users, SSL encryption, WCAG 2.1 compliance, mobile responsiveness

comment.undefined: System qualities like performance, security

comment.undefined: Development tools used in the project

comment.undefined: Final assessment of the completed project
